I"n<h1 id="how-do-i-add-environment-variables">How do I add environment variables</h1>

<p>to access the environment variable, use <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">$</code> dollar sign as prefix, e.g. <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">$MYVAR</code></p>

<p>To set variable <strong>only</strong> for current shell:
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">VARNAME="my value"</code>
To set it for current shell and <strong>all processes</strong> started from current shell:
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">export VARNAME="my value"      # shorter, less portable version</code>
To set it <strong>permanently</strong> for all future bash sessions add such line to your <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.bashrc</code> file in your $HOME directory.
To set it permanently, and <strong>system wide</strong> (all users, all processes) add set variable in  /etc/environment:
<code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">gksudo gedit /etc/environment</code>
You need to logout from current user and login again so environment variables changes take place.</p>
